\begin_layout Subsubsection
Changes in Theoretical Chapter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chapter has undergone a substantial rewrite.
 The model has been changed and solved analytically without resorting to
 any arbitrary probability functions of income mobility.
 Following is a summary of changes made in response to the suggestions made
 in the report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The model is related with a uniform distribution of performance-affecting
 variables in the population.
 The chapter no longer relates the model with contest theory.
 A contrast against the contest theory literature has also been added.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The scope of the model and its stated goals are narrowed.
 The crucial assumption of social goals tied with economic goals has been
 explained in greater detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A discount factor has been introduced in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The chapter clarifies that consumption is being viewed simply as an investment
 in mobility related consumption.
 Due to economic goals being assumed as being tied with social goals, the
 scope of status investments is limited to those where such competitions
 of attributes are relevant.
 A tennis game analogy - which is similar to small-scale interviews or competiti
ons - has been explained in the introduction of the chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The chapter discusses important contributions to the literature - including
 Dugar, Bhattacharya & Reiley (2012), Moldovanu, Sela & Shi (2007), Truyts
 (2010) and Roychowdhury (2016).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Changes in First Empirical Chapter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the first empirical chapter is now the second chapter in the
 thesis.
 Following changes were made based on the suggestions in the report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It has been explained that the relationship of household permanent income
 with consumption of high-quality food is only relevant for exploring how
 status consumption may be limited to richer households.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The choice of Tanzania has been discussed in more detail.
 The sociological evidence for food carrying status in the Tanzanian society
 has also been discussed in detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The mentions of intergenrational wealth have been removed from the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Charts and Figures have been corrected based on the suggestions in the report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Changes in Second Empirical Chapter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the second empirical chapter is now the third chapter in the
 thesis.
 Following changes were made based on the suggestions in the report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The chapter introduction explains that the exploration of the role of household
 permanent income (total expenditure) is the main purpose of the empirical
 analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The chapter explains that education is not considered aspirational in the
 strictest sense but is only explored as consumption of status value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The attempts to measure urbanisation have been dropped.
 Instead, the local wealth measure is discussed as one of the main explanatory
 variables - leaving urban-rural distinctions only as a means to compare
 the analysis with a more conventional one.
 As suggested in the report, the chapter no longer discusses asset ownership
 as the measure of urbanisation or of concentration of assets.
 Instead, average assets in the district are discussed plainly as a measure
 of local wealth.
 This approach had been one of the choices that were suggested in the examiners'
 report.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The discussion of asset-density has been removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The analysis focuses on the household permanent income as one of the explanatory
 variables - instead of presenting permanent income as a means to under
 wealth effects on education.
 The wealth effects are still mentioned in the chapter - but only to motivate
 the use of household permanent income as one of the main explanatory variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As suggested in the report, a summary for Behrman and Knowles (1999) paper
 as well as Glewwe & Jacoby (2004) has been added.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An explanation of why Tanzania and Nigeria were chosen for the analysis
 is provided.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample selection issue and the issue of endogeneity (due to education
 expenditure occurring both in the dependent variable and independent variable)
 have been explained in the chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The mentions of intergenrational wealth have been removed from the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The explanations for why mother's education wasn't used has been added.
 The number of secondary-schools per district are explained as one of the
 control variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
References to causality have been avoided while keeping the focus on the
 exploration of the role of household permanent income on education expenditure.
\end_layout

